516–1607","1510":"1510","1584":"1584","1494":"1494","1607":"1607","January 1516":"January 1516","1490":"1490","1538":"1538","1516":"1516","1515":"1515","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Scotland","Canongate, Midlothian, Scotland":"Canongate, Midlothian, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fairley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of several places called from Old English <i>fæger</i> ‘beautiful’ or <i>fearn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Primarily from Fairlie in Ayrshire, but perhaps occasionally from other places similarly named, such as Fairley (Northumberland), Fairlee in Newport (Isle of Wight) and Fairliehope (Linton, Peeblesshire). A Scots family once known as <i>de Ros</i> adopted the name <i>Fairlie</i> when granted lands at Fairlie, Ayrshire by Robert the Bruce.","Irish: variant of   Farrelly  , from <i>Ó Fearghaile</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Farrelly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Clodagh, Fintan, Kieran.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fearghaile</b>, from <i>Fearghaile</i>, the longer genitive form of the personal name <i>Fearghal</i> ‘man of valour’ (see   Farrell  )."]},{"name":"Fairlie","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of several places in Scotland so called (see   Fairley  ).","Possibly also an Americanized form of South German <b>Fährle</b>, <b>Värli</b>: metonymic occupational name for a hog farmer, from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>varch</i> ‘pig, piglet’."]},{"name":"Fairly","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: variant of   Fairley   or   Fairlie  ."]},{"name":"Fairleigh","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: possibly a variant of Scottish   Fairley  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. If not simply an invention, it may have been devised as a feminine equivalent of   Alan   (of which it is an anagram), or a shortened form of   Alana .  It seems to have been first used by the American film actress  Lana Turner  (  1920–1995 ), whose original name was  Julia ."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Isabelle Fairley was born in 1494, in Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Sir William Majorbankis in 1510, in Edinburgh, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1584, in her hometown, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1494–1584":"1494–1584","1490–1538":"1490–1538","1515–Male":"1515–Surnud","1516–1607":"1516–1607","1510":"1510","1584":"1584","1494":"1494","1607"